+# Glossary
+
+Every word other orgs-reins docs use, in one sentence each, in plain
+language. If a term you saw on a screen is not here, please open an
+issue — that is a doc bug.
+
+Terms are grouped so that a reader skimming for "the word my agent just
+said at me" can find it by context. If you prefer alphabetical, your
+browser's `Ctrl-F` works fine.
+
+---
+
+## The big picture
+
+- **Agent** — an AI program that takes actions on your behalf, like
+  editing files, running shell commands, or calling outside services.
+  Claude Code, OpenClaw, Hermes, and Replit Agent are all agents (or
+  hosts for agents).
+
+- **Runtime** — the product the agent runs inside of. The runtime is what
+  shows you the chat window, executes the agent's tool calls, and exposes
+  the integration points Reins plugs into. Claude Code is a runtime;
+  OpenClaw is a runtime; this repo ships per-runtime sub-skills under
+  [`skills/`](../skills/) as they get written.
+
+- **Reins** — the security-control layer that sits between your agent and
+  whatever it is about to do, decides whether to allow it, and writes the
+  outcome down. See [pegasi-ai/reins](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins).
+
+- **Reins Cloud** — the web app at `app.pegasi.ai` your admin uses to
+  push org-wide policy and review audit data across the team. Connect
+  during `reins init`; the agent on your laptop keeps enforcing even if
+  Reins Cloud is unreachable
+  ([upstream skill](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/plugin/skills/reins/SKILL.md)).
+
+---
+
+## How Reins plugs in
+
+- **Hook** — a small program your AI runtime runs before or after every
+  agent action. Reins ships as a hook so it can interpose on every action
+  the agent tries to take.
+
+- **PreToolUse** — the hook that fires *before* the agent runs an action,
+  giving Reins the chance to block it. Exit code `2` from a PreToolUse
+  hook is what stops the action
+  ([upstream `src/hooks/pre-tool-use.ts`](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/src/hooks/pre-tool-use.ts)).
+
+- **PostToolUse** — the hook that fires *after* an action has run. It
+  cannot stop the action — it just records what happened, in the audit
+  log
+  ([upstream `src/hooks/post-tool-use.ts`](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/src/hooks/post-tool-use.ts)).
+
+- **MCP (Model Context Protocol)** — the standard way modern agents talk
+  to outside services like Notion, Gmail, or your database. If the agent
+  is reading your inbox or writing to a Notion page, it is going through
+  MCP, and Reins's MCP rules apply.
+
+---
+
+## How Reins decides
+
+- **Policy** — the file that lists which actions to allow, warn on, ask
+  about, or block. Defaults are sensible; your admin can tighten or
+  loosen them. Lives at `~/.openclaw/reins/policy.json`.
+
+- **Module** — a category of thing the agent can touch. `FileSystem`,
+  `Shell`, `Browser`, `Gateway`, `Network`, and `MCP` are the modules
+  Reins ships with. Each module has methods.
+
+- **Method** — a specific action inside a module. `FileSystem.write`
+  means "the agent is trying to write a file"; `Shell.bash` means "the
+  agent is trying to run a shell command."
+
+- **Rule** — one entry in the policy: a module, a method, and what to do
+  when that method is invoked. The shape is defined by `SecurityRule` in
+  [upstream `src/types.ts`](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/src/types.ts).
+
+- **Action** — what a rule says to do. One of three values:
+  - `ALLOW` — just run it, do not interrupt.
+  - `ASK` — pause and prompt a human yes/no.
+  - `DENY` — refuse outright.
+  Defined as `Decision` in
+  [upstream `src/types.ts`](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/src/types.ts).
+
+- **Decision** — what Reins logged after evaluating an action: `ALLOWED`,
+  `BLOCKED`, or (rarer) `WARN`. The decision is what shows up in
+  `reins audit`. Easy to confuse with **action** above, which is what the
+  policy *says* to do; the decision is what actually *happened*.
+
+- **Severity** — a label Reins puts on blocked actions to indicate how
+  bad they were. The labels used in the source are `HIGH`, `CRITICAL`,
+  and `CATASTROPHIC`
+  ([upstream `src/hooks/pre-tool-use.ts`](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/src/hooks/pre-tool-use.ts)).
+  Some docs and UIs collapse these into `CRITICAL / HIGH / MEDIUM / LOW`
+  for end users — assume `CRITICAL` and `CATASTROPHIC` are the
+  unbypassable end of the spectrum on your machine.
+
+- **denyPaths** — a list of file-path patterns that get refused even if
+  the method's action is `ALLOW` or `ASK`. A reverse-allowlist for the
+  things you most want to protect. Implemented by `Interceptor` in
+  [upstream `src/core/Interceptor.ts`](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/src/core/Interceptor.ts).
+
+- **allowPaths** — the opposite of `denyPaths`: an explicit list of paths
+  that bypass an otherwise-restrictive rule. Useful for "the agent can
+  write anywhere under `~/workspace`, nowhere else."
+
+- **Glob pattern** — the syntax Reins uses for `denyPaths` and
+  `allowPaths`. `*` matches any chunk of a path segment, `**` matches any
+  number of segments (including across directories), `?` matches one
+  character, and `~` is expanded to your home directory. So
+  `~/.ssh/**` covers `~/.ssh/id_rsa` *and* `~/.ssh/keys/foo`.
+
+---
+
+## When something is blocked
+
+- **Block** — Reins refused to let the agent run an action because a
+  `DENY` rule (or a `denyPaths` entry) fired. The agent will see the
+  block and the runbook in [`when-blocked.md`](./when-blocked.md) covers
+  what to do next.
+
+- **Safe alternative** — the rephrased action Reins suggests when it
+  blocks something. Most blocks happen because the agent reached for the
+  blunt version of a request; the safe alternative is the targeted
+  version that does the same job without tripping the rule.
+
+- **Override** — accepting a non-critical block by pasting an explicit
+  approval token. Available only for `HIGH`-severity blocks, not for
+  `CRITICAL` or `CATASTROPHIC` ones, and only for rules the policy
+  flagged as user-overridable.
+
+- **`CONFIRM-` token** — the short six-character hex token Reins prints
+  when an override is available. Format `CONFIRM-XXXXXX`, generated per
+  block from a hash of the action being approved
+  ([upstream `src/core/Arbitrator.ts`](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/src/core/Arbitrator.ts)).
+  A token approves *this specific action* — pasting it again later does
+  not re-approve a different action.
+
+---
+
+## Record-keeping
+
+- **Audit log** — the append-only file at
+  `~/.openclaw/reins/decisions.jsonl` recording every decision Reins
+  made. View with `reins audit -n 50` or tail with
+  `tail -f ~/.openclaw/reins/decisions.jsonl`.
+
+- **`decisions.jsonl`** — the file path of the audit log. JSONL means
+  "one JSON object per line"; each line is one decision.
+
+- **Security scan** — the periodic configuration check Reins runs with
+  `reins scan`. Looks for things like exposed API keys, weak file
+  permissions, and missing TLS — see the check list in
+  [upstream `src/core/SecurityScanner.ts`](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/src/core/SecurityScanner.ts).
+  Reins's README describes the scan target as
+  ["OWASP ASI10" vulnerabilities](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/README.md);
+  the upstream docs do not expand the acronym, so we don't either.
+
+- **Drift** — a change in your configuration since the last saved scan.
+  `reins scan --monitor` compares against the previous baseline and
+  alerts when something moved
+  ([upstream `src/cli/scan.ts`](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/src/cli/scan.ts)).
+  An admin watching drift catches "someone disabled a hook" or "an API
+  key got committed" without having to look every day.
+
+---
+
+## For admins
+
+- **Org policy** — the highest-priority layer of rules, pushed from
+  Reins Cloud by your org's admin. CRITICAL rules in the org policy are
+  immutable on your laptop: a local edit cannot soften them.
+
+- **Team policy** — the second-priority layer, scoped to a team. Use it
+  for "the data team can talk to the database but the marketing team
+  cannot."
+
+- **Local override** — your own edits at
+  `~/.openclaw/reins/policy.json`. Apply unless a higher-priority layer
+  marked a rule immutable.
+
+- **Built-in defaults** — the lowest-priority layer, baked into Reins.
+  Used when no higher layer has spoken on a method. Reads `ALLOW`,
+  writes `ASK`, deletes `DENY`
+  ([upstream `src/config.ts`](https://github.com/pegasi-ai/reins/blob/main/src/config.ts)).
+
+- **Merge order** — the rule for which layer wins on a conflict, highest
+  to lowest: org policy → team policy → local override → built-in
+  defaults. Cloud being unreachable does *not* fail open; the last
+  cached cloud policy is still enforced.
+
